<TITLE> Indian strike halts trade at Bhomra port </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Satkhira, July 6 (bdnews24.com)The export-import activities at Bhomra land port have come to a halt following an indefinite strike at the Indian side of the port, an official said on Monday. The Clearing and Forwarding Agents' Association of Ghojadanga, on the Indian part of the port, called the strike on Monday following a clash between the agents and truck drivers on July 1. The assistant commissioner of Bhomra customs confirmed the strike and said, "We have heard that the authorities on the Indian side were meeting with feuding groups in the morning." Kazi Nowshad Delwar Raju, general secretary of Bhomra Clearing and Forwarding Agents' Aassociation, said Achintya Kumar, general secretary of Ghojadanga association, sent them a letter asking for assistance to make the strike success. On July 1, the agents and truck drives clashed over parking of a truck in front of the Ghojadanga C&F office. Five men including the president of the association Bholanath Ghose, Moslem Ali, Bidyut Gazi and Prashanta Banerjee were injured. bdnews24.
